    "answer": "Based on the search results, paying for external research for a new agent CFO project may be justified if it addresses critical needs such as spend visibility, procurement compliance, or strategic insights, especially when internal resources or expertise are limited. Recent articles emphasize the importance of procurement metrics and spend visibility for CFOs, which can be complex and costly to develop in-house ([Arkestro, 2026](https://arkestro.com/blog/8-spend-visibility-metrics-every-cfo-should-track-in-2026)). Outsourcing research can provide timely, reliable data that supports decision-making and strategic planning.\n\nAdditionally, outsourcing research is recommended when internal teams lack the skills or capacity to conduct comprehensive market or internal analysis efficiently ([Relevant Insights, 2022](https://www.relevantinsights.com/articles/when-is-it-time-for-outsourcing-research)). The decision should consider opportunity costs, internal credibility, and the potential for faster, more accurate insights from specialized external providers.\n\n**Recommendation:** If the research will significantly impact strategic decisions, cost management, or compliance, and internal capabilities are insufficient, purchasing external research is justified. Otherwise, evaluate if internal resources can meet the project's needs effectively. Given the importance of procurement metrics and spend visibility highlighted in recent reports, external research can be a worthwhile investment for a new agent CFO project.",
